content.description: Start on the same jug as the left sit start for the traverse or ante up, but head left through the rail and crimps, out to a big slot, left arete, then up and back right along the lip to the obvious, flat jug. A tricky lip encounter gets you over and a chossy 5.9 gets you to the top of the boulder. The rock's not amazing, but the moves are good. There's about twenty of 'em, and it's a big pretty boulder.
content.location:
This is on the power endurance boulder on the backside of

Tim's Finn

.

content.description: The crux comes at the end, the overhanging crack system.  The first placement is fairly high, but you can nest a couple small/medium-sized nuts together then a relatively easy runout with a small amount of groundfall potential that leads to multiple seriously awesome cam placements. Sack up and go for it.
content.protection: You can simply bring 1 small/medium nut (I think I used a #9 and a #7) and a #0.5 and #0.75 BD Camalots.
content.location: This is on the Northern side of the Hummingbird Boulders area. It is on a massive boulder with an obvious crack system, there is a small bush in it low.
